sonal identity, and the national territories we occupy merely stages on which historical processes and political rituals are enacted? Or do the forms of buildings and streets, the evocative sensibilities of architecture and vista, the aesthetics of place conjured in art and media constitute political landscapes—broad sets of spatial practices critical to the formation, operation, and overthrow of polities, regimes, and institutions? Smith brings together contemporary theoretical developments from geography and social theory with anthropological perspectives and archaeological data to pursue these questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLandscape archaeologyxPolitical aspects. 0aLandscape assessment. 0aPolitical anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aanthropological.  aarchaeologists.  aartistic works.  aclassicists.  acomplex societies.  acultural identity.  aearly societies.  aepigraphs.  aformation of governments.  aformation of polities.  amaya.  anational territories.  anations.  anonfiction.  aoverthrow of regimes.  aphysical world.  apolitical anthropology.  apolitical formation.  apolitical history.  apolitical institutions.  apolitical landscape.  apolitical power.  apolitical rituals.  apolitical science.  asocial theory.  asystematic approach.  atextbooks.  aurartu.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023749040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093699740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936997/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB